result.execSummary:
The defendant Leroy Holland was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Burglary-(Trailer) [Modifiers: Party to a Crime], a class F felony, Wisconsin Statutes 943.10(1m)(d).
  • Theft-Movable Property >$5000-$10,000 [Modifiers: Party to a Crime], a class H felony, Wisconsin Statutes 943.20(1)(a).

Charge(s) in this case were read in to this or other case(s). A "read in" charge is a charge that is dismissed as part of a plea agreement, however:

  • The defendant agrees to have the court consider the charge(s) when sentencing for another crime, under Wis. Stats. 973.20(1g)(b); and
  • The defendant cannot be prosecuted for these charge(s) in the future.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

Defendant Leroy Holland in court with attorney Debra J. Patterson.  Tyrone Martin St Junior appeared for the State of Wisconsin.
  Deputy Court Clerk:  ss

On motion of the state, pursuant to plea negotiations, Court ordered COUNTS 3 and 4 DISMISSED BUT READ IN.

AS TO COUNTS 1 and 2:
  Defendant changes his plea to GUILTY.  Defendant examined as to his plea, advised of his Constitutional Rights and the maximum penalty.  Court found that defendant knowingly, voluntarily and intelligently waived his rights.  Plea questionnaire received and filed.  Parties stipulate to the complaint as a factual basis to sustain defendant's plea.  Court found defendant guilty as charged in the Information and ordered a Judgment of Conviction be entered on the record.  Court advised defendant that as a convicted felon he may not possess any firearms.

AS TO COUNT 1:
  Sentencing proceeds.  Statements made by the State, defense counsel and defendant.
:
Court sentenced defendant to serve a term of IMPRISONMENT in the Wisconsin State Prisons for 6 YEARS.  INITIAL CONFINEMENT of 3 YEARS and EXTENDED SUPERVISION of 3 YEARS. Credit given for zero days  time served if revoked.
.
COURT STAYS sentence and places defendant on PROBATION for 3 YEARS.
.
CONDITIONS OF PROBATION/EXTENDED SUPERVISION: 
-No new violations of law rising to probable cause
-AODA assessment and cooperate with any programs deemed necessary by the probation department;
-absolute sobriety, no alcohol, no drugs;
-random urine screens;

-pay restitution in the amount to be determined;

-provide a DNA sample if one has not previously been provided; pay the cost by the end of this sentence
-Pay all costs, fees, surcharges and assessments associated with this case.  Payment in full by the end of this sentence.  Failure to pay will result in the entry of a civil judgement.

-no contact with  2900 N 112th St.  (WE Energies);  United Scrap
.

Defendant is not eligible for Challenge Incarceration Program.
Defendant is not eligible for the Wisconsin Substance Abuse Program.

AS TO COUNT 2:

Court ordered the defendant to serve 12 MONTHS in the House of Correction, CONSECUTIVE, with credit for 1 day time served.  Huber release for work and/or school
